One person can spread the virus to a lot of people before they even realise they have it. Equally one person can break the chain of infection by washing their hands frequently, not touching surfaces, wearing an effective mask, or simply deciding to phone a friend rather than go to a bar.
We all need to look at our lives & change our behaviours now to reduce the likelihood that we will unknowingly catch & spread the virus. It is no good waiting untill the virus is known to be near our area as that may well be too late, we may have come into contact already. We need to make changes now in order to make ourselves a more difficult environment for the virus.
Look at your life & decide on some simple short-term changes you could make today.
Could you :-
Work from home more?
Ensure cleaners at your workplace are using effective anti-microbial products & routines?
Clean your own workspace carefully & suggest others do?
Have less face to face meetings (especially those business breakfasts in cafes) & more business conversations on the phone/ Skype?
Do not touch things in others workspaces & do not enter others offices unless you need to?
Ask your boss to supply anti-microbial wipes to clean equipment that is used by more than person. Use the wipes before & after use?
When out & about maintain awareness of what you touch & try to avoid touching railings, handles, products you are not actually going to buy etc?
Carry tissues, a bag for disposal, & hand cleansing gel (for those times you are not near a sink) use them every time you touch your face or touch others. Use hand gel after touching ticket machines etc?
Consider buying an effective mask for use in crowds & public areas?
Cultivate awareness of when you touch your face & avoid it if possible. Wear a mask to remind yourself if necessary?
Wash your hands immediately when you arrive at home/work/someone elses home etc?
Travel at less busy times & wear disposable gloves for the duration of the journey & bin them on arrival?
Consider swapping leisure activities for less virus friendly ones e.g go for a walk in a garden with one friend, instead of bowling with a group, phone a friend instead of meeting, exercise at home whilst chatting over Skype?
Stand & sit a bit further from others when talking?
Encourage family, friends & workmates to wash hands frequently?
If you start coughing or sneezing stay at home or wear a mask or at least wrap a scarf around your face. Change the scarf frequently & put used ones into a polythene bag, wash with hot soapy water. Help out friends & workmates who are staying home because they are coughing or sneezing. Provide them with essentials but stay well back from the door?
Stock up on essentials so you can stay in if you think you may have come into contact with the virus. When you are thinking that is no time to be having to go to the supermarket?
Stay away from big gatherings & travel less generally?
Make less trips to the supermarket but be more efficient in getting what you need when you do? Wash food items coming into your home?
Arrange a local group of parents who collaborate to temporarily educate their children in small groups, instead of school, using information books etc from the school?
Take anti-microbial spray or wipes with you to the gym & clean parts of the equipment you will come into contact with before & after use?
This is not a definitive list, just suggestions for ways we could become less virus friendly as a population. Even if we just choose a few things each & do them we will as a population be making ourselves a more virus resistant environment. Do something!
BE THE BARRIER NOT THE CARRIER. All the best everyone.
